{
  "texts": [
    "However, as far as we know, all known examples of expanding Ricci solitons with constant scalar curvature are locally homogeneous.",
    "Our aim in this article is to construct, in each dimension n ≥ 4, infinite families depending on an arbitrary large number of parameters, of expanding Ricci solitons with constant negative scalar curvature that are not locally homogeneous.",
    "The underlying manifolds are diffeomorphic to a so-called twisted principal bundle: a Lie group bundle(3)M n = B × ρ N -→ B 2,over a closed surface, with fibre a simply-connected nilpotent Lie group N. More precisely, M is the total space of the associated bundle to the universal cover B → B corresponding to a representation ρ ∈ Hom(π 1 (B), Aut(N)); see Section 2 for details.",
    "Locally, there is a free N-action that is transitive on fibres, which in general cannot be extended to a well-defined action on the total space due to the global twist by ρ.It turns out that the solitons in this article have additional structure: they are all affine expanding solitons.",
    "In essence, this means that they are complete, the local N-actions are isometric, and the diffeomorphisms η t: M → M driving the Ricci flow evolution are bundle maps that act as automorphisms on the fibres: see Definition 6.1 for a precise definition."
  ]
}